  "prompt": "Does India contribute to the ISS (International Space Station)?",
  "response": "India does not have a direct role in the construction or operation of the International Space Station (ISS). The primary contributors to the ISS are the United States, Russia, Europe, Japan, and Canada. However, India has been engaging in space research and has its own space station plans in the works.\n\nThat being said, Indian astronauts could potentially visit the ISS in the future. In 2020, the United States and India signed the Artemis Accords, which is a set of principles and guidelines for cooperation in space exploration. This agreement could open up opportunities for Indian astronauts to visit the ISS as part of joint missions.\n\nAdditionally, India has been collaborating with other space agencies on various projects. For example, ISRO (Indian Space Research Organisation) has worked with NASA on the Mars Orbiter Mission and the NISAR (NASA-ISRO Synthetic Aperture Radar) satellite. These collaborations could potentially lead to further cooperation on projects related to the ISS.",
